{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646955"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18218"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18218"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10932"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96311"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBone remodelling requires coordinated activity between bone-forming osteoblasts and bone-resorbing osteoclasts. The development of osteoclasts is tightly regulated by signalling molecules produced by other bone cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is primarily responsible for stimulating osteoclast development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibroblast growth factor 2","Calcium-sensing receptor","Receptor activator of nuclear factor kappa-B ligand","Wnt protein","Dickkopf-related protein 1"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOsteoclasts are specialised cells responsible for bone resorption, playing a crucial role in bone remodelling. Their development is influenced by various factors released by other bone cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe development of osteoclasts is primarily mediated by \u003Cstrong\u003Ereceptor activator of nuclear factor kappa-B ligand (RANKL)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is released from preosteoblasts. RANKL binds to its receptor RANK on osteoclast precursors, promoting their differentiation into mature osteoclasts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium-sensing receptor\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in calcium homeostasis rather than directly in osteoclast development. \u003Cstrong\u003EDickkopf-related protein 1\u003C/strong\u003E functions as an inhibitor of the Wnt signalling pathway and is not directly involved in osteoclastogenesis. \u003Cstrong\u003EWnt protein\u003C/strong\u003E signalling is more associated with osteoblast activity rather than osteoclast development. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibroblast growth factor 2\u003C/strong\u003E participates in various cellular processes but does not specifically regulate osteoclast differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["RANKL is a key factor released by preosteoblasts that stimulates the development of osteoclasts.","Osteoclasts are responsible for bone resorption, a critical process in bone remodelling.","The interaction between RANKL and its receptor RANK on osteoclast precursors is essential for osteoclast differentiation."],"references":["Khurana I, Khurana A, Kowlgi NG. Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2019.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 80; pg. 996"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96311"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96311"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:56:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:56:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10932"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attribute